Part 1: Getting some Data¶

Here we take a look at the Mongomery County Police Department's database of founded crime. All crime founded since July 1st 2016 found in Montgomery County are contained within this dataset.

Part 3: Combining Parts 1 and 2¶

Here we will try to visulaize this dataset in a way that allows us to interpret it better. We also limit the number of rows that we look at so that my PC doesn't blow up.

In [65]:
crime_table["Crime Name1"].unique()
Out[65]:
array(['Crime Against Society', 'Crime Against Property',
       'Crime Against Person', 'Other', 'Not a Crime', nan], dtype=object)
In [66]:
sample = crime_table.sample(2000)
for index, crime in sample.iterrows():
    if crime["Crime Name1"] == "Crime Against Society":
        folium.Circle(location=[crime["Latitude"], crime["Longitude"]],
                    color='red', fill=True).add_to(map_osm)
        
    if crime["Crime Name1"] == 'Crime Against Property':
        folium.Circle(location=[crime["Latitude"], crime["Longitude"]],
                    color='green', fill=True).add_to(map_osm)
        
    if crime["Crime Name1"] == 'Crime Against Person':
        folium.Circle(location=[crime["Latitude"], crime["Longitude"]],
                    color='blue', fill=True).add_to(map_osm) 
        
map_osm

Even though we have seperated the crimes based on who was impacted, but this is little to no help in helping us understand the dataset any better than before. Other than the fact that more poplulous areas have more crimes.

Let's look at just the crimes commited ageinst other people to help us further limit our data.

In [67]:
sample2 = crime_table[crime_table["Crime Name1"] == "Crime Against Person"].sample(2000)
sample2["Crime Name2"].unique()
Out[67]:
array(['Simple Assault', 'Forcible Rape', 'Fondling',
       'Human Trafficking, Commercial Sex Acts', 'Aggravated Assault',
       'All Other Offenses', 'Forcible Sodomy', 'Forcible Fondling',
       'Kidnapping/Abduction', 'Sexual Assault With An Object',
       'Intimidation', 'Murder and Nonnegligent Manslaughter',
       'Statuory Rape'], dtype=object)

We will split the sub-categories of this crime class into 3 further sub-categories.

In [68]:
sexual_assult = ['Forcible Rape','Fondling','Sexual Assault With An Object', 'Forcible Fondling','Statuory Rape','Forcible Sodomy']
kidnapping = ['Human Trafficking, Commercial Sex Acts','Human Trafficking, Involuntary Servitude','Kidnapping/Abduction']
attacks = ['Simple Assault', 'Aggravated Assault','Murder and Nonnegligent Manslaughter', 'Justifiable Homicide','Negligent Manslaughter']

The 'sexual_assult' category includes any crime that has to do with unwanted advances onto another person.

The 'kidnapping' category include any crime that has to do with taking a persons for any reason (human trafficing, kidnapping for ransom, etc.

The 'attacks' category include any crime that has to do with physical assult, minus any crimes that are a part of the 'sexual_assult' category (which is physical assult, but of a different nature).

In [69]:
map_osm_2 = folium.Map(location=[39.13, -77.2], zoom_start=9.5)

for index, crime in sample2.iterrows():
    if crime["Crime Name2"] in sexual_assult:
        folium.Circle(location=[crime["Latitude"], crime["Longitude"]],
                    color='red', fill=True).add_to(map_osm_2)
        
    if crime["Crime Name2"] in kidnapping:
        folium.Circle(location=[crime["Latitude"], crime["Longitude"]],
                    color='green', fill=True).add_to(map_osm_2)
        
    if crime["Crime Name2"] in attacks:
        folium.Circle(location=[crime["Latitude"], crime["Longitude"]],
                    color='blue', fill=True).add_to(map_osm_2) 
        
map_osm_2

Finally, we can make some sort of conclusion on the dataset that is crime in Montgomery County.

Looking at our new visualization, we can clearly see that the majority of crime commited in the greater Montgomery area is of physical assult nature. A lot less sexual assult crimes are commited in the county, and even less crimes that have to do with kidnapping happen.

It it obvious, but I still feel the need to mention the fact that the more dense an area is, the more crime that occurs in that area. This applies to all crimes, not just the ones that are commited ageinst other people (as mentioned previously).
